      "content": "Historians primarily frame the UN's ineffectiveness as a specific failure of its structural design and international legitimacy, particularly the veto power that allows great powers to block collective action. Rather than viewing this as an inevitable flaw of the modern world order, many argue that the organization was built on a post-WWII assumption of great power cooperation that has increasingly become untenable. This structural rigidity is seen as a deliberate choice by a few dominant states rather than an unavoidable consequence of global politics, leaving the UN to manage symptoms rather than resolve root causes.",
